riters]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American television news anchors]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:American Unitarians]] \n[[Category:Baseball statisticians]]\n[[Category:Television anchors from Boston]]\n[[Category:Current TV people]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:NBC News people]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences alumni]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball broadcasters]]\n[[Category:National Football League announcers]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from New York City]]\n[[Category:People from Hastings-on-Hudson, New York]]\n[[Category:Progressivism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:WCVB-TV]]\n[[Category:Hackley School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "216.49.37.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Olbermann"}
{"title_page": "Chapatsu", "text_new": "[[File:A fashionable boy in Japan.jpg|right|thumb|An example of the chapatsu (Japanese boy).]]\n[[File:\u30e4\u30f3\u30de\u30deP6014882a.jpg|right|thumb|The brown hair also became popular with [[Yanmama]] (young mother). ]]\n{{nihongo|'''Chapatsu'''|\u8336\u9aea/\u3061\u3083\u3071\u3064}}, literally \"[[tea]] [[hair]]\" in the [[Japanese language]],<ref name=\"kokugo\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Kokugo Daijiten |title=\u8336\u9aea |trans-title=Chapatsu |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |oclc=56431036 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref> is a style of [[Bleach (chemical)|bleach]]ing (and occasionally [[dye]]ing) hair, found among [[Japan]]ese [[teen]]s. The style was once banned at Japanese schools and became a widespread topic of the [[civic right]] to self-expression, but discussion of the topic died down due to the ubiquity of the style.<ref name=\"imidas\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Imidas |title=\u8336\u9aea |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shueisha |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Chapatsu |oclc=506996961 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web-japan.org/trends98/honbun/ntj990202.html|title=Brown But Not Brazen|date=3 February 1999|publisher=Trends in Japan|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe word ''Chapatsu'' is formed from two [[kanji]]: {{linktext|\u8336}}, meaning \"[[tea]]\" and {{linktext|\u9aea}}, meaning \"hair\".<ref name=\"kokugo\" /> ''Chapatsu'' originally referred to a variety of colors of hair dye, including [[blonde]], [[red]], [[Orange (colour)|orange]], and [[blue]], it now refers to a brown-tea [[hue]].<ref name=\"dijitaru\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Dijitaru Daijisen |title=\u8336\u9aea |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Chapatsu |oclc=56431036 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref> In [[Japanese language|Japanese]] the word is also frequently written in [[hiragana]] [[syllabary]].\n\n== Style ==\n[[File:Yumi Yoshimura 2009 (02).jpg|thumb|right|160px|Japanese singer [[Yumi Yoshimura]] with a ''chapatsu''.]]\nWhile the style itself began to show up in [[Tokyo]] streets during the early to mid-1990s, ''chapatsu'' was first described in [[Imidas]], an annual publication of new words and concepts in the Japanese language, in 1997. ''Chapatsu'' did not appear in ''[[K\u014djien]]'', an authoritative dictionary of the Japanese language, until 1998. The style first gained popularity among adolescent girls, seeking to accentuate their tanned skin (rebelling against more traditional definitions of beauty), but quickly grew into the mainstream.<ref name=\"imidas\" />\nby the mid 2000s, however trends  seemed to indicate that the \"chapatsu\" as a mainstream style was on its way out.<ref>[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/culture/waiwai/archive/news/2006/12/20061206p2g00m0dm007000c.html Dyejobs make for the nearest stylist as hair experts proclaim black is back] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309161625/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/culture/waiwai/archive/news/2006/12/20061206p2g00m0dm007000c.html |date=March 9, 2008 }}</ref>  however, though it died out as youth centered fashion trend  of rebellion, Chapatsu came to be accepted not only on young people but also in certain business settings, and it was established before long as one of the Japanese fashions.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ganguro]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Chapatsu}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070320053909/http://brokenstones.at.infoseek.co.jp/fashion/dmv.html Transcript of Speech by Nomura Masaichi of the National Museum of Ethnology on Chapatsu and Ganguro fashions]\n\n[[Category:Japanese fashion]]\n[[Category:Hair coloring]]\n\n\n{{Japan-culture-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:A fashionable boy in Japan.jpg|right|thumb|An example of the chapatsu (Japanese boy).]]\n[[File:\u30e4\u30f3\u30de\u30deP6014882a.jpg|right|thumb|The brown hair also became popular with [[Yanmama]] (young mother). ]]\n{{nihongo|'''Chapatsu'''|\u8336\u9aea/\u3061\u3083\u3071\u3064}}, literally \"[[tea]] [[hair]]\" in the [[Japanese language]],<ref name=\"kokugo\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Nihon Kokugo Daijiten |title=\u8336\u9aea |trans-title=Chapatsu |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |oclc=56431036 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref> is a style of [[Bleach (chemical)|bleach]]ing (and occasionally [[dye]]ing) hair, found among [[Japan]]ese [[teen]]s. The style was once banned at Japanese schools and became a widespread topic of the [[civic right]] to self-expression, but discussion of the topic died down due to the ubiquity of the style.<ref name=\"imidas\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Imidas |title=\u8336\u9aea |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shueisha |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Chapatsu |oclc=506996961 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web-japan.org/trends98/honbun/ntj990202.html|title=Brown But Not Brazen|date=3 February 1999|publisher=Trends in Japan|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe word ''Chapatsu'' is formed from two [[kanji]]: {{linktext|\u8336}}, meaning \"[[tea]]\" and {{linktext|\u9aea}}, meaning \"hair\".<ref name=\"kokugo\" /> ''Chapatsu'' originally referred to a variety of colors of hair dye, including [[blonde]], [[red]], [[Orange (colour)|orange]], and [[blue]], it now refers to a brown-tea [[hue]].<ref name=\"dijitaru\">{{cite encyclopedia|encyclopedia=Dijitaru Daijisen |title=\u8336\u9aea |url=http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |accessdate=2012-07-26 |year=2012 |publisher=Shogakukan |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Chapatsu |oclc=56431036 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070825113418/http://rekishi.jkn21.com/ |archivedate=2007-08-25 }}</ref> In [[Japanese language|Japanese]] the word is also frequently written in [[hiragana]] [[syllabary]].\n\n== Style ==\n[[File:Yumi Yoshimura 2009 (02).jpg|thumb|right|160px|Japanese [[J-rock]] singer [[Yumi Yoshimura]] with an ''chapatsu''.]]\nWhile the style itself began to show up in [[Tokyo]] streets during the early to mid-1990s, ''chapatsu'' was first described in [[Imidas]], an annual publication of new words and concepts in the Japanese language, in 1997. ''Chapatsu'' did not appear in ''[[K\u014djien]]'', an authoritative dictionary of the Japanese language, until 1998. The style first gained popularity among adolescent girls, seeking to accentuate their tanned skin (rebelling against more traditional definitions of beauty), but quickly grew into the mainstream.<ref name=\"imidas\" />\nby the mid 2000s, however trends  seemed to indicate that the \"chapatsu\" as a mainstream style was on its way out.<ref>[http://mdn.mainichi.jp/culture/waiwai/archive/news/2006/12/20061206p2g00m0dm007000c.html Dyejobs make for the nearest stylist as hair experts proclaim black is back] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309161625/http://mdn.mainichi.jp/culture/waiwai/archive/news/2006/12/20061206p2g00m0dm007000c.html |date=March 9, 2008 }}</ref>  however, though it died out as youth centered fashion trend  of rebellion, Chapatsu came to be accepted not only on young people but also in certain business settings, and it was established before long as one of the Japanese fashions.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ganguro]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|Chapatsu}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070320053909/http://brokenstones.at.infoseek.co.jp/fashion/dmv.html Transcript of Speech by Nomura Masaichi of the National Museum of Ethnology on Chapatsu and Ganguro fashions]\n\n[[Category:Japanese fashion]]\n[[Category:Hair coloring]]\n\n\n{{Japan-culture-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Xfansd", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chapatsu"}
{"title_page": "Chick Young", "text_new": "{{About|the journalist|the American cartoonist|Chic Young}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Chick Young\n| alt                       = \n| birth_name                = Charles Young\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|5|4}}\n| birth_place               = [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]]\n| occupation                = Journalist\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Charles \"Chick\" Young''' (born 4 May 1951)<ref>{{cite episode|title=Sportsound |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0079g4q |series=[[Sportsound]] |credits=Presenters: [[Richard Gordon (broadcaster)|Richard Gordon]] |network=BBC |station=BBC Radio Scotland |location=Glasgow\n|airdate=30 April 2011 |work=BBC News |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> is a professional [[association football]] [[pundit (expert)|pundit]] who regularly appears for [[BBC Scotland]] on ''[[Sportscene]]'' and ''[[Sportsound]]''.  He is known for his trademark laugh and speech patterns, which have made him a popular target for lampooning on the BBC Scotland sports comedy ''[[Only an Excuse?]]'' Young is a Rangers F.C fan\n\n==Career==\nYoung has become a prominent football commentator with the BBC.  He started hosting episodes of ''Sportsound'' in October 2009, working two to three episodes a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00nh63z/episodes |title=BBC Radio Scotland - Sportsound: Chick Young's World of Football - Episodes |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref> In addition, he regularly writes his own view on Scottish football matches and players in his online column with the BBC, titled, \"Chick Young's View\".\n\nIn 2008, he was injured in a game between MSPs in Glasgow.  He was tackled and his ankle was badly hurt, forcing him to miss a charity golf event the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/disgraceful-foul-mouthed-thugs-that-s-our-footballing-msps-according-to-chick-young-1-1139136|title=Disgraceful, foul-mouthed  thugs \u2013 that's our footballing MSPs, according to Chick  Young|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Young made a guest appearance as himself in the Scottish police comedy series ''[[Scot Squad]]''.\n\n== Personal life ==\nYoung was born in [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]]. His father died at the age of 47 from a [[heart attack]] when Young was six years old.  He attended [[Bellahouston Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio/play/p06fch5r|title=BBC Radio Scotland - 21 Jul 18 Billy MacBain and David Scott|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Young married [[Sally Carr]], lead singer of 70s pop group Middle of the Road, and had a son, Keith, in 1980. They separated in 1984, but did not divorce, and remained friends. His son Keith died at the age of 20 in 2001 in a road accident when his motorcycle was hit by a driver on the [[A8 road (Scotland)|A8]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mgalba.com/en/features/archive/chick-young-cuideri.html |title=Mg Alba |publisher=Mg Alba |accessdate=13 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312151731/http://www.mgalba.com/en/features/archive/chick-young-cuideri.html |archivedate=12 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | last = Deveney | first = Catherine | url = http://living.scotsman.com/tvradio/Father-and-Sons.2299797.jp | title = Father and Sons | publisher = Scotsman.com Living | date = 3 February 2002 | accessdate =12 January 2010 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish association football commentators]]\n[[Category:Scottish sportswriters]]\n[[Category:People from Govan]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bellahouston Academy]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-tv-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the journalist|the American cartoonist|Chic Young}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Chick Young\n| alt                       = \n| birth_name                = Charles Young\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1951|5|4}}\n| birth_place               = [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]]\n| occupation                = Journalist\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Charles \"Chick\" Young''' (born 4 May 1951)<ref>{{cite episode|title=Sportsound |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0079g4q |series=[[Sportsound]] |credits=Presenters: [[Richard Gordon (broadcaster)|Richard Gordon]] |network=BBC |station=BBC Radio Scotland |location=Glasgow\n|airdate=30 April 2011 |work=BBC News |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> is a professional [[association football]] [[pundit (expert)|pundit]] who regularly appears for [[BBC Scotland]] on ''[[Sportscene]]'' and ''[[Sportsound]]''.  He is known for his trademark laugh and speech patterns, which have made him a popular target for lampooning on the BBC Scotland sports comedy ''[[Only an Excuse?]]''\n\n==Career==\nYoung has become a prominent football commentator with the BBC.  He started hosting episodes of ''Sportsound'' in October 2009, working two to three episodes a month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00nh63z/episodes |title=BBC Radio Scotland - Sportsound: Chick Young's World of Football - Episodes |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=13 October 2012}}</ref> In addition, he regularly writes his own view on Scottish football matches and players in his online column with the BBC, titled, \"Chick Young's View\".\n\nIn 2008, he was injured in a game between MSPs in Glasgow.  He was tackled and his ankle was badly hurt, forcing him to miss a charity golf event the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/disgraceful-foul-mouthed-thugs-that-s-our-footballing-msps-according-to-chick-young-1-1139136|title=Disgraceful, foul-mouthed  thugs \u2013 that's our footballing MSPs, according to Chick  Young|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Young made a guest appearance as himself in the Scottish police comedy series ''[[Scot Squad]]''.\n\n== Personal life ==\nYoung was born in [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]]. His father died at the age of 47 from a [[heart attack]] when Young was six years old.  He attended [[Bellahouston Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio/play/p06fch5r|title=BBC Radio Scotland - 21 Jul 18 Billy MacBain and David Scott|website=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Young married [[Sally Carr]], lead singer of 70s pop group Middle of the Road, and had a son, Keith, in 1980. They separated in 1984, but did not divorce, and remained friends. His son Keith died at the age of 20 in 2001 in a road accident when his motorcycle was hit by a driver on the [[A8 road (Scotland)|A8]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mgalba.com/en/features/archive/chick-young-cuideri.html |title=Mg Alba |publisher=Mg Alba |accessdate=13 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312151731/http://www.mgalba.com/en/features/archive/chick-young-cuideri.html |archivedate=12 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web | last = Deveney | first = Catherine | url = http://living.scotsman.com/tvradio/Father-and-Sons.2299797.jp | title = Father and Sons | publisher = Scotsman.com Living | date = 3 February 2002 | accessdate =12 January 2010 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, Chick}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish association football commentators]]\n[[Category:Scottish sportswriters]]\n[[Category:People from Govan]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bellahouston Academy]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-tv-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "185.58.166.46", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chick_Young"}
{"title_page": "Pacifica High School (Garden Grove, California)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = Pacifica High School\n| image = Pacifica HS logo.png\n| image_size = 200px\n| motto = \n| established = 1965\n| type = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n| enrollment = 1,660 (2017\u201318)<ref name=NCES>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=0614880&SchoolPageNum=4&ID=061488001868|title=Pacifica High|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| ratio = 24.06<ref name=NCES/>\n| staff = 69.00 (FTE)<ref name=NCES/>\n| mascot = Sea (Bull)Dog\n| colors = Black, white, and blue\n| conference = [[Empire League]]\n| district = [[Garden Grove Unified School District]]\n| superintendent = Gabriela Mafi\n| principal = Steve Osborne<ref>http://www.gghs.us/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=566410&type=u&pREC_ID=865601</ref>\n| streetaddress = 6851 Lampson Avenue\n| city = [[Garden Grove, California|Garden Grove]]\n| state = California\n| zipcode = 92845\n| country = United States\n| coordinates = {{coord|33|46|53|N|118|0|49|W|display=inline,title}}\n| yearbook = The Reef\n| nickname = Mariners\n| website = [http://www.pacificamariners.com/ School website]\n| picture = \n}}\n'''Pacifica High School''' is a high school in [[Garden Grove, California]] and is a member of the [[Garden Grove Unified School District]]. Pacifica High School first opened its doors in 1965, and since then Pacifica has enrolled more than two thousand students each year.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/jun/03/news/ss-56667 | work=Los Angeles Times | date=June 3, 1998 | title=Pacifica High}}</ref> One of Pacifica's most valuable landmarks on campus is the Navy Anchor placed in the quad. Initially painted blue until repainted black in 2011, the anchor was donated by the U.S Navy.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/>\n\n==Athletics==\nPacifica's sports teams are called the Mariners, and compete in [[Empire League]] of the [[California Interscholastic Federation]]'s [[CIF Southern Section|Southern Section]]. Prior to 2006, they competed in the Garden Grove League with the other schools in the district.\n\nSports offered are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pacificamariners.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=219173&type=d&pREC_ID=489195 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 15, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150617015752/http://www.pacificamariners.com/apps/pages/index.jsp?uREC_ID=219173&type=d&pREC_ID=489195 |archivedate=June 17, 2015 }}</ref>\n{{div col}}\n*Football (boys)\n*Cross Country (girls and boys)\n*Tennis (girls & boys)\n*Volleyball (girls & boys)\n*Waterpolo (girls & boys)\n*Basketball (girls & boys)\n*Soccer (girls & boys)\n*Wrestling (boys)\n*Baseball (boys)\n*Softball (girls)\n*Swim (Coed)\n*Track (Coed)\n*Golf\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Orchestra ==\nThe Pacifica High School Orchestra in 2018\u20132019 received a superior at the SCSBOA Regional Festivals, held at Garden Grove California.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} In that same year, the high school orchestra also received a unanimous superior at DSUSD (Desert Sands Unified School District).{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n==Marching band and drumline==\nIn 2005\u20132009 and in 2003, The Pacifica [[Marching band]]'s [[Drumline]] took the SCPA (Southern California Percussion Alliance) gold medal, and in 2006\u20132009, took the WGI (Winter Guard International) World Championship gold medal in the PSO (Percussion Scholastic Open) division, along with numerous first-place finishes throughout Southern California.  Pacifica also finished with an SCPA Bronze medal in 2004 and a WGI silver medal in 2005.  The Pacifica drumline is the second ensemble to ever capture four consecutive WGI World Championship gold medals.<ref>[http://wgi.org/events/scores/pscwchamps.php] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704065732/http://wgi.org/events/scores/pscwchamps.php |date=July 4, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n\n'''<big><u>Naval Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps</u></big>'''\n\nThe Pacifica High School NJROTC is one of 65 programs in Area 11 which includes Southern California and Arizona.  The unit began in 1996 and has averaged 120 cadets annually.  The program's mission is to promote citizenship development and success after graduation.  Unit Awards include:  Area Manager Award (2016), Unit Achievement (2004, 2005, 2006, 2011, 2013, 2015, 2017), Distinguished Unit (2007, 2008), and a Distinguished Unit with Academic Honors (2010, 2018, 2019).  The program was also recognized as the , Area 11 Most Improved Unit 2019.  \n\nCadets are able to participate in numerous teams including:  Drill, Physical Fitness, Orienteering (Land Navigation), Brain Brawl (Academic), Cyberpatriot, Sea Perch, Academic Quizbowl, and Marksmanship.   The unit has competed in the following Area 11 (State/Region Championships):  <u>Brain Brawl</u> (2010-2020) winning the Championship in 2020, <u>Orienteering</u> (2018, 2019, 2020) winning the California State Championship in 2020, <u>Cyberpatriot</u> (2019, 2020), <u>Drill, Academic, Fitness Meet</u> (2004, 2006, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020).  The unit has also competed at the National Level in the following competitions:  Brain Brawl (2014 - 6th, 2016 -12th, 2019 - 7th, 2020), Orienteering (2019 - 15th, 2020), and Drill, Academic, Fitness (2020).  \n\nCadets have been accepted to numerous colleges and universities in California and throughout the United States including Brown University, Rice, and Cornell.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n<!-- \"notable\" is not what they did in school, their pasttimes, or other hobbies, but what they are famous for on a national level, not locally, and can be verified.  Yea that isn't correct either.  Notability means they qualify to have a biography on wikipedia.  no more, no less. -->\n{{