{"title_page": "Kenneth Waller", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{for|American bodybuilder|Ken Waller}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Kenneth Waller\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1927|11|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]], West Riding of Yorkshire, England<ref name=book>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PlO5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA154|last=Walker|first=Craig|title=On The Buses: The Complete Story|year=2011|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|isbn=9781908382849}}</ref><ref name=archive>[http://cuttingsarchive.org/index.php/Kenneth_Waller_obituary Kenneth Waller obituary]</ref>\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|2000|1|28|1927|11|5}}\n| death_place = London, England\n| occupation = Television actor\n| years_active = 1959\u20131998\n}}\n'''Kenneth Waller''' (5 November 1927 \u2013 28 January 2000)<ref>[http://people.theiapolis.com/actor-2VDS/kenneth-waller/ Kenneth Waller]</ref> was an English actor.  He was known for portraying Grandad in ''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' and [[List of Are You Being Served? characters#The Grace brothers (Harold Bennett and Kenneth Waller) (series 1\u20138, series 8)|Old Mr. Grace]] in ''[[Are You Being Served?]]''\n\n==Early life==\nKenneth Waller was born in [[Huddersfield]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]] on 5 November 1927.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> In his childhood he moved to [[Southampton]] and was living there at the breakout of [[World War II]].\n\nIn 1949, he was a member of the Christ Church Woodhouse men's choir.<ref>{{cite web|title=Family history: Alan and Elaine Danielson\u2019s memories of Christ Church, Woodhouse men\u2019s choir.|date=29 June 2011|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/lifestyle/nostalgia/family-history-alan-elaine-danielsons-4974631|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving in the [[Royal Air Force]], Waller worked for a firm of auctioneers.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==Career==\n\nExperience in local rep at the [[Oxford Playhouse]] encouraged him to move to London, where he made his West End debut in [[Julian Slade]] and [[Dorothy Reynolds]]' 1957 musical ''[[Free as Air]]''.  He was later in the original cast of ''[[Give a Dog a Bone]]'' in 1964, and took over various roles in various other London productions such as ''[[Salad Days (musical)|Salad Days]]'' and ''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Musical]]''.  Waller was also associated the [[Open Air Theatre, Regent's Park]], but always looked forward to the times when his work took him on location further afield, including Rome, [[India]] and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nAn excellent pianist and an ardent lover of classical and choral music, Waller was extremely knowledgeable on the subject of oratorio and sang with Anthony Bowles' Actors' choir and the [[BBC Chorus]].  He also appeared as the Narrator in ''[[Peter and the Wolf]]'', and [[Carl Davis]] wrote a special concert piece, \"Duck's Diary,\" for him.<ref name=archive/>\n\nFrom the fifties to the seventies, his career as an actor saw him appear on both television and film.  On the big screen, he had modest roles in ''[[Room at the Top (1959 film)|Room at the Top]]'' (1959), ''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]'' (1968), ''[[Scrooge (1970 film)|Scrooge]]'' (1970), ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1971) and ''[[Carry On Behind]]'' (1975).  Other small screen credits included ''[[Big Deal (TV series)|Big Deal]]'', ''[[Crossroads (UK TV series)|Crossroads]]'', ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]'', ''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'', ''[[Z-Cars]]'', ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]'', ''[[Doctor Who]]'', ''[[All Creatures Great and Small (TV series)|All Creatures Great and Small]]'', ''[[Terry and June]]'' and  ''[[Juliet Bravo]]''.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> Waller also portrayed the father of [[Curly Watts]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref name=archive/>\n\nIn 1981, he joined the cast of ''[[Are You Being Served?]]'' as Old Mr. Grace.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWaller also made an appearance in the [[On the Buses (series 5)|Series 5]] episode, \"Boxing Day Social\", on ''[[On the Buses]]'', as well appearing in the 1984 miniseries, ''[[Ellis Island (miniseries)|Ellis Island]]'' and even lending his voice for ''[[Romuald the Reindeer]]''.<ref name=book/><ref>[http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/1583986/kenneth-waller Hollywood.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Waller became a household name as Grandad in [[Carla Lane]]'s [[Liverpool]] sitcom, ''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' and his catchphrase, \"Where's my tea?\", quickly caught on with the viewing public.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWaller continued to stay in touch with the theatre during the final years of his life, touring successfully with [[Barbara Windsor]] in [[Joe Orton]]'s classic black comedy, ''[[Entertaining Mr Sloane]]'' and appearing in a musical version of ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' at the [[Manchester Opera House]], in 1998.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDespite his television fame, Waller never lost his affection for Yorkshire, taking great pride in retaining both his accent and his many friends within the Huddersfield Choral Society.<ref name=archive/>\n\nKenneth Waller died on 28 January 2000 in London, England at the age of 72, after a brief illness.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> He was unmarried.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==TV and filmography==\n*''Romuald the Reindeer'' (voice, 1996)\n*''Arthur Watts, [[Curly Watts]]'s father'' Coronation Street (1988).\n*''[[Boon (TV series)|Boon]]'' \"Mr. Newell\" (1987)\n*''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' \"Grandad\" (1986\u201391)\n*''[[The Pickwick Papers (TV series)|The Pickwick Papers]]'' \"Mr. Fogg\" (1985)\n*''The Beiderbecke Affair'' \"Harry the Supergrass\" (1985)\n*''Roll Over Beethoven'' \"Mr. Beckett\" (1985)\n*''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' \"Roland\" in episode \"A Number of Old Wives Tales\" (1984)\n*''[[Ellis Island]]'' \"Shepherd #1\" (1984)\n*''Big Deal'' \"Ferret\" (1984)\n*''Fair Ground!'' \"Mr. Grant\" (1983)\n*''[[Juliet Bravo]]'' \"Sidney Dorkins\" in episode \"Where There's Muck...\" (1982)\n*''[[Are You Being Served?]]'' \"Old Mr. Henry Grace\" (1981)\n*''[[All Creatures Great and Small (TV series)|All Creatures Great and Small]]'' \"Mr. Beresford\", the bank manager, in episode \"Every Dog His Day...\" (1980) and \"Charity Begins at Home\" (1980)\n*''[[The Mayor of Casterbridge]]'' \"Clerk of Court\" (1978)\n*''[[The Famous Five (1978 TV series)|The Famous Five]]'' \"Enemy Agent\" (1978)\n*''[[Z-Cars]]'' \"Wilfred Wilson\" (1977)\n*''[[Target (UK TV series)|Target]]'' \"Warehouse Transport Manager\" (1977)\n*''[[Doctor Who]]'' \"Hedges\" in episode ''[[The Invisible Enemy (Doctor Who)|The Invisible Enemy]]'' (1977)\n*''[[The Venetian Twins]]'' (1976)\n*''Doctor on the Go'' \"Mr. Pole\" (1975)\n*''[[Carry On Behind]]'' \"Barman\" (1975)\n*''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' \"Dealer\" (1974)\n*''[[Menace (TV series)|Menace]]'' \"Manager\" (1973)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Pianist\" (1972)\n*''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' \"Porter\" (1972)\n*''[[On the Buses]]'' \"Busman\" (1971)\n*''[[Fiddler on the Roof (film)|Fiddler on the Roof]]'' uncredited (1971)\n*''[[The Onedin Line]]'' \"Drayman\" in episode \"The High Price\" (1971)\n*''[[The Love Pill]]'' \"Professor Edwards\" (1971)\n*''The Onedin Line'' \"Drayman\" (uncredited) in episode \"Other Points of the Compass\" (1971)\n*''[[Scrooge (1970 film)|Scrooge]]'' (uncredited) \"Party Guest\" (1970)\n*''[[Softly, Softly (TV series)|Softly, Softly]]'' \"Potter\" (1970)\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang (film)|Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]'' \"Inventor\" (1968)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Fred Jones\" (1968)\n*''A Game of Murder'' \"Dr. Hasting\" (1966)\n*''[[Crossroads (UK TV series)|Crossroads]]'' \"Mr. Hardgreaves\" (1964)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Stanley Collins\" (1963)\n*''[[Room at the Top (1959 film)|Room at the Top]]'' \"Reggie\" (uncredited) (1959)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0909060|name=Kenneth Waller}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waller, Kenneth}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{for|American bodybuilder|Ken Waller}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name       = Kenneth Waller\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=y|1927|11|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Huddersfield]], West Riding of Yorkshire, England<ref name=book>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PlO5BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA154|last=Walker|first=Craig|title=On The Buses: The Complete Story|year=2011|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|isbn=9781908382849}}</ref><ref name=archive>[http://cuttingsarchive.org/index.php/Kenneth_Waller_obituary Kenneth Waller obituary]</ref>\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|2000|1|28|1927|11|5}}\n| death_place = London, England\n| occupation = Television actor\n| years_active = 1959\u20131998\n}}\n'''Kenneth Waller''' (5 November 1927 \u2013 28 January 2000)<ref>[http://people.theiapolis.com/actor-2VDS/kenneth-waller/ Kenneth Waller]</ref> was an English actor.  He was known for portraying Grandad in ''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' and [[List of Are You Being Served? characters#The Grace brothers (Harold Bennett and Kenneth Waller) (series 1\u20138, series 8)|Old Mr. Grace]] in ''[[Are You Being Served?]]''\n\n==Early life==\nKenneth Waller was born in [[Huddersfield]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]] on 5 November 1927.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> In his childhood he moved to [[Southampton]] and was living there at the breakout of [[World War II]].\n\nIn 1949, he was a member of the Christ Church Woodhouse men's choir.<ref>{{cite web|title=Family history: Alan and Elaine Danielson\u2019s memories of Christ Church, Woodhouse men\u2019s choir.|date=29 June 2011|url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/lifestyle/nostalgia/family-history-alan-elaine-danielsons-4974631|accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter serving in the [[Royal Air Force]], Waller worked for a firm of auctioneers.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==Career==\n\nExperience in local rep at the [[Oxford Playhouse]] encouraged him to move to London, where he made his West End debut in [[Julian Slade]] and [[Dorothy Reynolds]]' 1957 musical ''[[Free as Air]]''.  He was later in the original cast of ''[[Give a Dog a Bone]]'' in 1964, and took over various roles in various other London productions such as ''[[Salad Days (musical)|Salad Days]]'' and ''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Musical]]''.  Waller was also associated the [[Open Air Theatre, Regent's Park]], but always looked forward to the times when his work took him on location further afield, including Rome, [[India]] and [[Scandinavia]].<ref name=archive/>\n\nAn excellent pianist and an ardent lover of classical and choral music, Waller was extremely knowledgeable on the subject of oratorio and sang with Anthony Bowles' Actors' choir and the [[BBC Chorus]].  He also appeared as the Narrator in ''[[Peter and the Wolf]]'', and [[Carl Davis]] wrote a special concert piece, \"Duck's Diary,\" for him.<ref name=archive/>\n\nFrom the fifties to the seventies, his career as an actor saw him appear on both television and film.  On the big screen, he had modest roles in ''[[Room at the Top (1959 film)|Room at the Top]]'' (1959), ''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]'' (1968), ''[[Scrooge (1970 film)|Scrooge]]'' (1970), ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' (1971) and ''[[Carry On Behind]]'' (1975).  Other small screen credits included ''[[Big Deal (TV series)|Big Deal]]'', ''[[Crossroads (UK TV series)|Crossroads]]'', ''[[The Fenn Street Gang]]'', ''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'', ''[[Z-Cars]]'', ''[[The Professionals (TV series)|The Professionals]]'', ''[[Doctor Who]]'', ''[[All Creatures Great and Small (TV series)|All Creatures Great and Small]]'', ''[[Terry and June]]'' and  ''[[Juliet Bravo]]''.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> Waller also portrayed the father of [[Curly Watts]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''.<ref name=archive/>\n\nIn 1981, he joined the cast of ''[[Are You Being Served?]]'' as Old Mr. Grace.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWaller also made an appearance in the [[On the Buses (series 5)|Series 5]] episode, \"Boxing Day Social\", on ''[[On the Buses]]'', as well appearing in the 1984 miniseries, ''[[Ellis Island (miniseries)|Ellis Island]]'' and even lending his voice for ''[[Romuald the Reindeer]]''.<ref name=book/><ref>[http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/1583986/kenneth-waller Hollywood.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Waller became a household name as Grandad in [[Carla Lane]]'s [[Liverpool]] sitcom, ''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' and his catchphrase, \"Where's my tea?\", quickly caught on with the viewing public.<ref name=archive/>\n\nWaller continued to stay in touch with the theatre during the final years of his life, touring successfully with [[Barbara Windsor]] in [[Joe Orton]]'s classic black comedy, ''[[Entertaining Mr Sloane]]'' and appearing in a musical version of ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' at the [[Manchester Opera House]], in 1998.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDespite his television fame, Waller never lost his affection for Yorkshire, taking great pride in retaining both his accent and his many friends within the Huddersfield Choral Society.<ref name=archive/>\n\nKenneth Waller died on 28 January 2000 in London, England at the age of 72, after a brief illness.<ref name=book/><ref name=archive/> He was unmarried.<ref name=archive/>\n\n==TV and Filmography==\n*''Romuald the Reindeer'' (voice, 1996)\n*''Arthur Watts, [[Curly Watts]]'s father'' Coronation Street (1988).\n*''[[Boon (TV series)|Boon]]'' \"Mr. Newell\" (1987)\n*''[[Bread (TV series)|Bread]]'' \"Grandad\" (1986\u201391)\n*''[[The Pickwick Papers (TV series)|The Pickwick Papers]]'' \"Mr. Fogg\" (1985)\n*''The Beiderbecke Affair'' \"Harry the Supergrass\" (1985)\n*''Roll Over Beethoven'' \"Mr. Beckett\" (1985)\n*''[[Minder (TV series)|Minder]]'' \"Roland\" in episode \"A Number of Old Wives Tales\" (1984)\n*''[[Ellis Island]]'' \"Shepherd #1\" (1984)\n*''Big Deal'' \"Ferret\" (1984)\n*''Fair Ground!'' \"Mr. Grant\" (1983)\n*''[[Juliet Bravo]]'' \"Sidney Dorkins\" in episode \"Where There's Muck...\" (1982)\n*''[[Are You Being Served?]]'' \"Old Mr. Henry Grace\" (1981)\n*''[[All Creatures Great and Small (TV series)|All Creatures Great and Small]]'' \"Mr. Beresford\", the bank manager, in episode \"Every Dog His Day...\" (1980) and \"Charity Begins at Home\" (1980)\n*''[[The Mayor of Casterbridge]]'' \"Clerk of Court\" (1978)\n*''[[The Famous Five (1978 TV series)|The Famous Five]]'' \"Enemy Agent\" (1978)\n*''[[Z-Cars]]'' \"Wilfred Wilson\" (1977)\n*''[[Target (UK TV series)|Target]]'' \"Warehouse Transport Manager\" (1977)\n*''[[Doctor Who]]'' \"Hedges\" in episode ''[[The Invisible Enemy (Doctor Who)|The Invisible Enemy]]'' (1977)\n*''[[The Venetian Twins]]'' (1976)\n*''Doctor on the Go'' \"Mr. Pole\" (1975)\n*''[[Carry On Behind]]'' \"Barman\" (1975)\n*''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' \"Dealer\" (1974)\n*''[[Menace (TV series)|Menace]]'' \"Manager\" (1973)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Pianist\" (1972)\n*''[[Dixon of Dock Green]]'' \"Porter\" (1972)\n*''[[On the Buses]]'' \"Busman\" (1971)\n*''[[Fiddler on the Roof (film)|Fiddler on the Roof]]'' uncredited (1971)\n*''[[The Onedin Line]]'' \"Drayman\" in episode \"The High Price\" (1971)\n*''[[The Love Pill]]'' \"Professor Edwards\" (1971)\n*''The Onedin Line'' \"Drayman\" (uncredited) in episode \"Other Points of the Compass\" (1971)\n*''[[Scrooge (1970 film)|Scrooge]]'' (uncredited) \"Party Guest\" (1970)\n*''[[Softly, Softly (TV series)|Softly, Softly]]'' \"Potter\" (1970)\n*''[[Chitty Chitty Bang Bang (film)|Chitty Chitty Bang Bang]]'' \"Inventor\" (1968)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Fred Jones\" (1968)\n*''A Game of Murder'' \"Dr. Hasting\" (1966)\n*''[[Crossroads (UK TV series)|Crossroads]]'' \"Mr. Hardgreaves\" (1964)\n*''Z-Cars'' \"Stanley Collins\" (1963)\n*''[[Room at the Top (1959 film)|Room at the Top]]'' \"Reggie\" (uncredited) (1959)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0909060|name=Kenneth Waller}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Waller, Kenneth}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Huddersfield]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Eagleash", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTV and Filmography:cap", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_Waller"}
{"title_page": "Earth 2 (album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Earth 2: Special Low Frequency Version\n| type         = [[Album]]\n| artist       = [[Earth (American band)|Earth]]\n| cover        = Earth2_album_cover.gif\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = February 5, 1993\n| recorded     = August 1992, at Avast Studios, Seattle, Washington\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Drone metal]], [[minimalist music|minimalism]], [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n| length       = 73:13\n| label        = [[Sub Pop]] <small>(SP185)</small>\n| producer     = [[Earth (American band)|Earth]], Stuart Hallerman\n| prev_title   = [[Extra-Capsular Extraction]]\n| prev_year    = 1991\n| next_title   = [[Phase 3: Thrones and Dominions]]\n| next_year    = 1995\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |first=Ned |last=Ragget |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r54435|pure_url=yes}}|title=Earth 2 |publisher=Allmusic |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Earth 2: Special Low Frequency Version''''', also known as simply '''''Earth 2''''', is the first full-length studio album by the [[drone metal]] band [[Earth (American band)|Earth]]. Produced by Earth and Stuart Hallerman, it was released on February 5, 1993, on [[Sub Pop|Sub Pop Records]]. The album was influential in the development of [[drone music]] and [[drone metal]] genres.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ARpE2IRKJXMC&pg=PA54&dq=%22Earth+2%22+drone+album&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Q8asUp3nA47Jswao5IHgDg&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Earth%202%22%20drone%20album&f=false | title=More than Words | journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=May 2011 | volume=27 | issue=4 | pages=54 | issn=0886-3032 }}</ref>  Celebrated as a \"milestone\" by ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]'''s [[Dayal Patterson]], he described it as \"a three-track, 75 minute deluge of feedback and distorted guitars that marked the blueprint for what lead singer/guitarist [[Dylan Carlson]] at the time coined 'ambient metal'\"<ref name=terrorizer>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=Dayal|title=A Spell in the Wilderness|journal=[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]|date=November 2005|issue=137|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nNed Raggett of [[Allmusic]] gave the album a positive review, stating: \"If [[Dylan Carlson|Carlson]] and his bassist du jour, in this case Dave Harwell, weren't quite Sub Pop's answer to the ranges of UK guitar extremism from the likes of [[Godflesh]], [[Main (band)|Main]], and [[Skullflower]], Earth still came pretty darn close to it, creating a record even the [[Melvins]] would find weird.\" He added: \"''Earth 2'' dedicates itself to the proposition that there's no such thing as too loud, trudging, or doom-laden.\" while describing the closing track as \"[[ambient music]] completely and totally suffused with threat and fuzz.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n[[Alan Licht]], in his third list of minimalist classics,<ref>http://rootstrata.com/rootblog/?p=135</ref> wrote \"Unlike a lot of more recent noise underground stuff, which (to me) is relatively factorable, this is technically boggling drone music--the sustain is achieved not just with distortion but through overdubbing, and there's clean guitars in there too--even on headphones it's hard to tell what the fuck they're really doing. On this album, Earth set up a drone and place a few choice metal riffs against it over the course of forty minutes, at which point they just let the drone chord ring for another half hour... Hard to remember how completely unfashionable this was in the heyday of [[grunge]]...\"\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1  = Seven Angels\n| length1 = 15:38\n| title2  = Teeth of Lions Rule the Divine\n| length2 = 27:04\n| title3  = Like Gold and Faceted\n| length3 = 30:31\n| total_length = 73:13\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Dylan Carlson]] \u2013 guitar\n*Dave Harwell \u2013 bass guitar\n*Joe Burns \u2013 percussion on \"Like Gold and Faceted\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.thronesanddominions.com/}}\n\n{{Earth (American band)}}\n\n[[Category:1993 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Earth (American band) albums]]\n[[Category:Sub Pop albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Earth 2: Special Low Frequency Version\n| type         = [[Album]]\n| artist       = [[Earth (American band)|Earth]]\n| cover        = Earth2_album_cover.gif\n| border       = yes\n| alt          = \n| released     = February 5, 1993\n| recorded     = August 1992, at Avast Studios, Seattle, Washington\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Drone metal]], [[minimalist music|minimalism]], [[Ambient music|ambient]]\n| length       = 73:13\n| label        = [[Sub Pop]] <small>(SP185)</small>\n| producer     = [[Earth (American band)|Earth]], Stuart Hallerman\n| prev_title   = [[Extra-Capsular Extraction]]\n| prev_year    = 1991\n| next_title   = [[Phase 3: Thrones and Dominions]]\n| next_year    = 1995\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |first=Ned |last=Ragget |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r54435|pure_url=yes}}|title=Earth 2 |publisher=Allmusic |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Earth 2: Special Low Frequency Version''''', also known as simply '''''Earth 2''''', is the first full-length studio album by the [[drone metal]] band [[Earth (American band)|Earth]]. Produced by Earth and Stuart Hallerman, it was released on February 5, 1993, on [[Sub Pop|Sub Pop Records]]. The album was influential in the development of [[drone music]] and [[drone metal]] genres.<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ARpE2IRKJXMC&pg=PA54&dq=%22Earth+2%22+drone+album&hl=tr&sa=X&ei=Q8asUp3nA47Jswao5IHgDg&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Earth%202%22%20drone%20album&f=false | title=More than Words | journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=May 2011 | volume=27 | issue=4 | pages=54 | issn=0886-3032 }}</ref>  Celebrated as a \"milestone\" by ''[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]'''s Dayal Patterson, he described it as \"a three-track, 75 minute deluge of feedback and distorted guitars that marked the blueprint for what lead singer/guitarist [[Dylan Carlson]] at the time coined 'ambient metal'\"<ref name=terrorizer>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=Dayal|title=A Spell in the Wilderness|journal=[[Terrorizer (magazine)|Terrorizer]]|date=November 2005|issue=137|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nNed Raggett of [[Allmusic]] gave the album a positive review, stating: \"If [[Dylan Carlson|Carlson]] and his bassist du jour, in this case Dave Harwell, weren't quite Sub Pop's answer to the ranges of UK guitar extremism from the likes of [[Godflesh]], [[Main (band)|Main]], and [[Skullflower]], Earth still came pretty darn close to it, creating a record even the [[Melvins]] would find weird.\" He added: \"''Earth 2'' dedicates itself to the proposition that there's no such thing as too loud, trudging, or doom-laden.\" while describing the closing track as \"[[ambient music]] completely and totally suffused with threat and fuzz.\"<ref name=\"allmusic\"/>\n\n[[Alan Licht]], in his third list of minimalist classics,<ref>http://rootstrata.com/rootblog/?p=135</ref> wrote \"Unlike a lot of more recent noise underground stuff, which (to me) is relatively factorable, this is technically boggling drone music--the sustain is achieved not just with distortion but through overdubbing, and there's clean guitars in there too--even on headphones it's hard to tell what the fuck they're really doing. On this album, Earth set up a drone and place a few choice metal riffs against it over the course of forty minutes, at which point they just let the drone chord ring for another half hour... Hard to remember how completely unfashionable this was in the heyday of [[grunge]]...\"\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| title1  = Seven Angels\n| length1 = 15:38\n| title2  = Teeth of Lions Rule the Divine\n| length2 = 27:04\n| title3  = Like Gold and Faceted\n| length3 = 30:31\n| total_length = 73:13\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Dylan Carlson]] \u2013 guitar\n*Dave Harwell \u2013 bass guitar\n*Joe Burns \u2013 percussion on \"Like Gold and Faceted\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.thronesanddominions.com/}}\n\n{{Earth (American band)}}\n\n[[Category:1993 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Earth (American band) albums]]\n[[Category:Sub Pop albums]]\n", "name_user": "Annecremin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding link to Dayal Patterson", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earth_2_(album)"}
{"title_page": "New Classical architecture", "text_new": "{{short description|Architectural movement}}\n{{About|the contemporary movement|the historical style|Neoclassical architecture}}\n[[File:Chicago Library Downtown.png|thumb|[[Harold Washington Library]] in [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois, USA]], 1991, by [[Thomas H. Beeby|HBRA Architects]]]]\n'''New Classical architecture''', '''New Classicism''' or the '''New Classical movement''' is a contemporary movement in architecture that continues the practice of [[Classical architecture]]. It can be considered as the modern continuation of [[Neoclassical architecture]]<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Curl|first1=James Stevens|author-link1=James Stevens Curl|chapter=New Classicism|chapter-url=https://books.google.it/books?id=4Lu6BwAAQBAJ|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Architecture|last2=Wilson|first2=Susan|date=2015|pages=520\u2013522|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967498-5|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Curl, James Stevens, 1937-|title=A dictionary of architecture and landscape architecture|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Curl, James Stevens, 1937-|isbn=978-0-19-280630-7|edition=2nd|location=Oxford [England]|oclc=64585874}}</ref>. The design and construction of buildings in this tradition is continuous throughout the twentieth and twenty-first centuries, even as [[Modernism|modernist]] and other post-classical theories of architecture have been more dominant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/new-classical-architecture |title=Inside Architecture's New Classicism Boom |last=Quigley |first=Kathleen |website=[[Architectural Digest]] |language=en |access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:Schermerhorn.jpg|thumb|[[Schermerhorn Symphony Center]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] \u2013 opened in 2006]]\nIn Britain, architect [[Raymond Erith]] continued to design classical houses into the late 1960s and early 1970s. [[Quinlan Terry]], a New Classical Architect who continues to practice, was an employee, later a partner and now the successor of the late [[Raymond Erith]]. In the late 1970s several young architects in Europe began challenging modernist proposals in architecture and planning. To broadcast them, [[Leon Krier]] and [[Maurice Culot]] founded the ''Archives d'Architecture Moderne'' in [[Brussels]] and began publishing texts and counterprojects to modernist proposals in architecture and planning.<ref>Leon Krier and Maurice Culot, \"Counterprojets: Prefaces,\" (Brussels: Archives d'Architecture Moderne, 1980).</ref> It received a boost from the sponsorship of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], especially with [[The Prince's Foundation for Building Community]].<ref>Charles, Prince of Wales, \"A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture,\" (New York: Doubleday, 1989).</ref>\n\n[[File:Thomas Aquinas Chapel Facade 2.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chapel at [[Thomas Aquinas College]] by [[Duncan Stroik]] (completed in 2009)]]\n\nIn these years, [[postmodern architecture]] developed a critique of modernist architectural aesthetics.<ref name=McAlester>{{cite book|last=McAlester|first=Virginia Savage|title=A Field Guide to American Houses|year=2013|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|isbn=978-1-4000-4359-0|pages=664\u2013665, 668\u2013669}}</ref>  Among them were certain influential postmodernist architects such as [[Charles Moore (architect)|Charles Moore]], [[Robert Venturi]],<ref>Robert Venturi, \"Complexity and Contradiction in Architecture,\" (New York: Museum of Modern Art, 1966).</ref> and [[Michael Graves]],  who used classical elements as ironic motifs in order to criticize modernism's sterility. A broad spectrum of more than two dozen architects, theorists, and historians presented other alternatives to modernism.<ref>Andreas Papadakis and Harriet Watson, eds., \"New Classicism: Omnibus Volume,\" (London: Academy Editions, 1990).</ref> Among them were several serious New Classical architects who saw classicism as a legitimate mode of architectural expression, several of whom would later become Driehaus Prize Laureates, including some such as [[Thomas Beeby]] and [[Robert A.M. Stern]], who practice both in post modern as well as classical modes. Some postmodernist firms, such as Stern and Albert, Righter, & Tittman, fully moved from postmodern design to new interpretations of traditional architecture.<ref name=\"McAlester\" /> Thomas Gordon Smith, the 1979 Rome Prize laureate from the American Academy in Rome, was a devotee of Charles Moore. In 1988, Smith published \"Classical Architecture - Rule and Invention\", and, in 1989, was appointed to chair of the [[University of Notre Dame]] Department of Architecture, now the School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nd.edu/classicalarch/2012/09/28/many-canons-many-conversions/|title=Many Canons, Many Conversions -|website=blogs.nd.edu|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184453/http://blogs.nd.edu/classicalarch/2012/09/28/many-canons-many-conversions/|archivedate=29 October 2013}}</ref> Today, other programs exist which teach in part New Classical Architecture at the [[University of Miami]], [[Judson University]], [[Andrews University]] and beginning in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucdenver.edu/academics/colleges/ArchitecturePlanning/Documents/Christine%20Franck%20appointment.pdf |title=College of Architecture and Planning at CU Denver |accessdate=2013-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191200/http://www.ucdenver.edu/academics/colleges/ArchitecturePlanning/Documents/Christine%20Franck%20appointment.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-29 }}</ref>  the [http://cap.ucdenver.edu/carta Center for Advanced Research in Traditional Architecture] at the University of Colorado Denver.\n\nAlongside these academic and scholarly developments, a populist and professional manifestation of new classicism has existed and continues to develop. The 1963 demolition of [[McKim, Mead & White]]'s [[Pennsylvania Station (1910\u20131963)|Pennsylvania Railroad Station]] in [[New York City]] provoked the formation of [[Classical America]] and its regional chapters, led by [[Henry Hope Reed, Jr.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/on-the-town/how-henry-hope-reed-saved-architecture/17877/|title=How Henry Hope Reed Saved Architecture|website=The New York Sun|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020164252/http://www.nysun.com/on-the-town/how-henry-hope-reed-saved-architecture/17877|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref>  Classical America advocated the appreciation of classically inspired buildings and for the practice of contemporary classical and traditional design by teaching architects to draw the classical orders, hosting walking tours, educational events, conferences and publishing The Classical America Series in Art and Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/classical-america-series-in-art-and-architecture/|title=Books - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620084212/http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/classical-america-series-in-art-and-architecture/|archivedate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the then-named Institute of Classical Architecture merged with Classical America to form the Institute of Classical Architecture & Classical America (now the [[Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]]). The ICAA currently supports and is supported by regional chapters across the United States, almost all of which host awards programs <ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.classicist.org/?cat=49|title=Articles - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=blog.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20131105150958/http://blog.classicist.org/?cat=49|archivedate=5 November 2013}}</ref> which recognize significant accomplishments in new classical and traditional design and construction.  The ICAA publishes ''[[The Classicist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/the-classicist/|title=Books - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010011101/http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/the-classicist/|archivedate=10 October 2017}}</ref> a peer-reviewed journal exclusively dedicated to the theory and practice of contemporary classicism in architecture, urbanism, and the allied arts.  The ICAA offers educational programs to architecture and design professionals, many of which follow the methodologies of the [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure des Beaux-Arts|\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]]. The ICAA also teaches courses to educate the general public,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/programs/|title=Calendar|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013011308/http://www.classicist.org/programs/|archivedate=13 October 2017}}</ref> and has created programs such as the Beaux Arts Atelier, the Advanced Program in Residential Design for the American Institute of Building Designers, and many other unique programs.\n\nThe international character of the New Classical movement was propelled by the creation in 2001 of the [[INTBAU|International Network for Traditional Building, Architecture & Urbanism (INTBAU)]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/feb/11/artsfeatures|title=Hooked on classics: in praise of traditional architecture|date=2002-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>, an international organization dedicated on supporting traditional building and the maintenance of local character<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/info/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. INTBAU has over 30 local chapters, which include countries like Albania, Afghanistan, Australia, Bangladesh, Canada, China, Cuba, Cyprus, Czechia, Estonia, Finland, Germany, India, Iran, Ireland, Italy, Malaysia, Montenegro, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Nigeria, Pakistan, the Philippines, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Russia, Spain, Sweden, Turkey and the USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/info/chapters/|title=Chapters {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. This network was created under the patronage of [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles of Wales]], himself an important figure in the New Classical movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.coinupdate.com/united-kingdom-new-crown-coin-celebrates-the-70th-birthday-of-hrh-charles-prince-of-wales/|title=United Kingdom: New crown coin celebrates the 70th birthday of HRH Charles, Prince of Wales {{!}} Coin Update|website=news.coinupdate.com|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, Chicago philanthropist [[Richard H. Driehaus]] established<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interactive.wttw.com/beeby/driehaus|title=The Driehaus Prize|date=7 March 2013|website=wttw.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023041011/http://interactive.wttw.com/beeby/driehaus|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref> a prize in architecture to be given to an architect \"whose work embodies the principles of classical and traditional architecture and urbanism in society, and creates a positive, long lasting impact.\"  Awarded by the [[Notre Dame School of Architecture|University of Notre Dame School of Architecture]], the [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]] is seen as the alternative to the modernist [[Pritzker Prize]]. The Driehaus Prize is given in conjunction with the [[Henry Hope Reed Award|Reed Award]], for an individual working outside the practice of architecture who has supported the cultivation of the traditional city, its architecture and art through writing, planning or promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Driehaus Prize Nomination Process|url=http://architecture.nd.edu/about/driehaus-prize/nomination-process/|publisher=University of Notre Dame School of Architecture|accessdate=11 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329102201/http://architecture.nd.edu/about/driehaus-prize/nomination-process/|archivedate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Other high-profiled classical architecture awards are the US-American [[Palladio Award]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Palladio Awards|url=http://www.palladioawards.com/|publisher=Active Interest Media|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406230208/http://palladioawards.com/|archivedate=6 April 2014}}</ref>, the [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] [[Rafael Manzano Prize]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiorafaelmanzano.com/en/|title=Premio Rafael Manzano de Nueva Arquitectura Tradicional|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>,  the [[Edmund N. Bacon Prize]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Edmund N. Bacon Prize|url=http://philadelphiacfa.org/lecture-bacon.php|publisher=Philadelphia Center for Architecture|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413172007/http://philadelphiacfa.org/lecture-bacon.php|archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref> and the [[Rieger Graham Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rieger Graham Prize|url=http://www.classicist.org/awards-and-prizes/rieger-graham-prize/|publisher=Institute of Classical Architecture & Art in New York|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413141627/http://www.classicist.org/awards-and-prizes/rieger-graham-prize/|archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref>  of the [[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]] (ICAA) for architecture graduates.\n\n== Institutions teaching New Classical Architecture ==\n<!--- Please sort alphabetically by location! References for curriculum welcome. --->\nWhile modernist teaching remains dominant at universities and architecture faculties around the world, some institutions focus solely, mainly or partly on teaching the principles of traditional and classical architecture and urban planning. Some of these are:<ref>[http://www.intbau.org/archive/academic.htm INTBAU] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728131429/http://www.intbau.org/archive/academic.htm |date=2015-07-28 }} - A guide to academic institutions/universities teaching New Urbanism and traditional/classical design. Retrieved 10 March 2015.</ref>\n\n;In India\n*Tirumala S.V. Institute of Traditional Sculpture and Architecture (SVITSA) in [[Tirupati]], [[Andhra Pradesh, India|Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>[http://www.tirumala.org Tirumala S.V. Institute of Traditional Sculpture and Architecture (SVITSA) in Tirupati] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202094950/http://www.tirumala.org// |date=2016-02-02 }}, India</ref>\n\n;In Italy\n* [[Polytechnic University of Bari]] in [[Bari]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/|title=Institutions {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n;In New Zealand\n*[[Unitec Institute of Technology|UNITEC Institute of Technology]] in [[Auckland]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/|title=Institutions {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n;In the United Kingdom\n*National Design Academy in [[Nottingham]] (heritage interior design)<ref>[http://www.nda.ac.uk/courses/Foundation-Degree-in-Heritage-Interior-Design.aspx National Design Academy Nottingham] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315035327/http://www.nda.ac.uk/courses/Foundation-Degree-in-Heritage-Interior-Design.aspx |date=2015-03-15 }}, degree course for heritage interior design</ref>\n*[[The Prince's Foundation for Building Community]] in [[London]]\n*[[The Prince's School of Traditional Arts]] in [[London]]\n*Unit 6 of the [[Kingston School of Art]]'s [[Master of Architecture]] program;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fada.kingston.ac.uk/al/march-architecture-unit-6-201516/|title=MArch Architecture \u2013 Unit 6 \u2013 2015/16|quote=''We will engage with the fundamental architectural considerations of scale and language, and the application of the order of classicism at the scale of the town, building, room and fitting.''|accessdate=13 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213165817/http://fada.kingston.ac.uk/al/march-architecture-unit-6-201516/|archivedate=13 February 2017}}</ref> the only postgraduate unit in the United Kingdom to teach classical design. Previously, this was taught in the undergraduate program.\n*[[University of Portsmouth]] in [[Portsmouth]], School of Architecture<ref>[http://www.port.ac.uk/media/contacts-and-departments/arch/project-office/ARCH---Project-Office---CPD---Design-Classical.pdf Portsmouth School of Architecture: Design Classical] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402182836/http://www.port.ac.uk/media/contacts-and-departments/arch/project-office/ARCH---Project-Office---CPD---Design-Classical.pdf |date=2015-04-02 }}. ''The school presents its award-winning course in the elements of classical design and how to\ndesign in the classical idiom, for CPD credits.'', PDF, retrieved 10 March 2015</ref>\n*[[PRASADA - Practice, Research, and Advancement in South Asian Design and Architecture]] at [[Welsh School of Architecture]], [[Cardiff University]] in Cardiff, Wales\n \n;In the United States\n[[File:Selwyn3.jpg|thumb|Ann's Court, [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] (designed by [[Porphyrios Associates]])]]\n*[[Andrews University#School of Architecture, Art & Design|Andrews University]] in [[Berrien Springs, Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrews.edu/saad/architecture/about/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616090857/http://www.andrews.edu/saad/architecture/about/|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 June 2012|title=Andrews University School of Architecture, Art & Design|quote=''Throughout the educational process, students are challenged to base architectural decisions on thoughtful and learned criteria, including the body of knowledge found within vernacular and classical traditions.''|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref> \n*[[Old Charleston Jail#American College of the Building Arts|American College of the Building Arts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buildingartscollege.us/|title=Welcome!|first=Chad|last=Urban|website=buildingartscollege.us|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150331002733/http://buildingartscollege.us/|archivedate=31 March 2015}}</ref> and School of the Arts at [[College of Charleston]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n*The Center for Advanced Research in Traditional Architecture at the [[University of Colorado]] in [[Denver]], Colorado\n*[[University of Miami]] in [[Miami|Miami, Florida]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arc.miami.edu/academics/certificates/index.html|title=Certificates {{!}} School of Architecture {{!}} University of Miami|website=arc.miami.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n*[[Yale School of Architecture]] in [[New Haven, Connecticut]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Salingaros, Nikos Angelos.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/57139148|title=Anti-architecture and deconstruction|date=2004|publisher=Umbau-Verlag|others=Alexander, Christopher, 1936-|isbn=3-937954-01-5|location=Solingen, Germany|oclc=57139148}}</ref>\n*[[Grand Central Academy of Art]] formerly hosted at the [[Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture & Art]] (ICAA) in [[New York City]], New York\n*[[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture & Art]] (ICAA) in [[New York City]], New York\n*[[Notre Dame School of Architecture|University of Notre Dame School of Architecture]] in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]]\n*[[Utah Valley University]] in [[Orem, Utah]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uvu.edu/aed/architecture/degrees-programs/bs-architecture.html|title=UVU Bachelor of Architecture {{!}} Bachelor of Architecture {{!}} Architecture and Engineering Design|website=www.uvu.edu|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*Beaux-Arts Academy in [[Salt Lake City]], Utah<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baa-utah.com/about/|title=Beaux-Arts Academy in Salt Lake City, classical architecture study programs|website=baa-utah.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314163529/http://www.baa-utah.com/about/|archivedate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Academy of Classical Design]] in Southern Pines, North Carolina\n\n==Examples==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Richmond_-_panoramio.jpg|[[Richmond, London|Richmond Riverside, London, England]], 1984\u201387, by [[Quinlan Terry]].\nFile:Main Plaza - Frankfurt Main - Germany - 02.jpg|''Main Plaza'', [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt, Germany]] by [[Hans Kollhoff]]\nFile:Brentwood_Cathedral_exterior_2.jpg|[[Brentwood Cathedral]], [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood, England]] by [[Quinlan Terry]]\nFile:Basshall.JPG|[[Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall]], [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth, Texas, USA]], 1998, by [[David M. Schwarz]]\nFile:Guadalupe_Shrine_Front.jpg|[[Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe]], [[La Crosse, Wisconsin|La Crosse, Wisconsin, USA]], 2004\u20132008, by [[Duncan G. Stroik]]\nFile:Queen_Mother_SQUARE,_Poundbury,_Dorset.jpg|[[Poundbury|Poundbury, England]], 1993, by [[L\u00e9on Krier]]\nFile:Moscow (8351273413).jpg|[[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Moscow|Ritz-Carlton Hotel]], [[Moscow|Moscow, Russia]], 2007, by Meerson Architects\nFile:Dallas Meadows Museum 1.jpg|[[Meadows Museum]], [[Dallas|Dallas, Texas, USA]], 2001, by [[Thomas H. Beeby|HBRA Architects]]\nFile:2013-05-12_London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg|[[RAF Bomber Command Memorial|Royal Air Force Bomber Command Memorial]], [[London|London, England]], 2012, by Liam O'Connor\nFile:Entrance_of_Queen's_Gallery,_Buckingham_Palace_(cropped).jpg|[[Queen's Gallery]], [[London|London, England]], 2002, by [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]]\nFile:Downing College in bright daylight.jpg|[[Downing College|Maitland Robinson Library]], [[Cambridge|Cambridge, England]], 1992, by [[Quinlan Terry]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture}}\n*[[New Urbanism]]\n*[[Revivalism (architecture)]]\n*[[Classical Realism]]\n*[[Driehaus Architecture Prize]]\n*[[Vernacular architecture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Christopher|title=The Timeless Way of Building|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H6CE9hlbO8sC|year=1979|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-502402-9}}\n*{{cite book|author=Charles, Prince of Wales|title=A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_FFIAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=978-0-385-26903-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Coles|first=William A.|title=Architecture in America: A Battle of Styles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vc4ZKS5uLNYC|year=1961|publisher=Ardent Media}}\n*{{cite book|last=Curl|first=James Stevens|title=Classical Architecture: An Introduction to Its Vocabulary and Essentials, with a Select Glossary of Terms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ub5D8cyl2AAC|year=2003|publisher=Norton|isbn=978-0-393-73119-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dodd|first=Phillip James|title=The Art of Classical Details: Theory, Design and Craftsmanship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tzlv-bsMT3kC|year=2013|publisher=Images Publishing|isbn=978-1-86470-203-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dowling|first=Elizabeth Meredith|title=New Classicism: The Rebirth of Traditional Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tsdPAAAAMAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Random House Incorporated|isbn=978-0-8478-2660-5}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gabriel|first=J. Fran\u00e7ois|title=Classical Architecture for the Twenty-first Century: An Introduction to Design|url=https://archive.org/details/classicalarchite0000gabr|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-73076-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gromort|first=Georges|title=The Elements of Classical Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4qp61EfFbzEC|year=2001|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-73051-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=Krier|first=L\u00e9on|title=Albert Speer: architecture, 1932-1942|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mE03AQAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Archives d'architecture moderne}}\n*{{cite book|last=Matrana|first=Marc R.|title=Lost Plantations of the South|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D1YfPjRCucQC|year=2009|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-469-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reed|first=Henry Hope|title=The Golden City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3kfFslzS50YC|date=1971|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-00547-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Scully|first=Vincent Joseph|title=The shingle style today: or, The historian's revenge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41xUAAAAMAAJ|year=1974|publisher=G. Braziller}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stroik|first=Duncan|title=The Church Building as a Sacred Place: Beauty, Transcendence, and the Eternal|year=2012|publisher=Liturgy Training Publications|isbn=978-1-59525-037-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=Summerson|first=John|title=The Classical Language of Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=57aoJE26kQkC|year=1963|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-69012-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Watkin|first=David|title=Morality and Architecture|url=https://archive.org/details/moralityarchitec0000watk|url-access=registration|year=1977|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-817350-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Neoclassical architecture}}\n* [http://www.doric-column.com/glossary_classical_architecture.html ''Illustrated Glossary of Classical Architecture'']\n* [http://www.classicist.org Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130609040947/http://www.traditionalarchitecture.co.uk/index.html Traditional Architecture Group]\n* [http://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/  INTBAU - Universities / institutions offering traditional architecture courses by country]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCco_r00ZJQ_46P5GPYguIvA/videos OpenSource Classicism] - project for free educational content about (new) classical architecture\n* [https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/10/the-architectural-trads-are-back-we-should-celebrate/ ''The architectural traditions are back \u2013 we should celebrate''], [[The Spectator]], Hugh Pearman, 28 October 2017\n\n;Examples\n* [https://www.flickr.com/groups/neohistorism/ Neohistorism Photo Group - New Classic Architecture]\n\n{{Archhistory}}\n{{Revivals}}\n{{Architecture in the United States}}\n[[Category:New Classical architecture| ]]\n[[Category:Classical architecture|*]]\n[[Category:Neoclassical architecture|\u00b7]]\n[[Category:Revival architectural styles]]\n[[Category:20th-century architectural styles]]\n[[Category:21st-century architectural styles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Architectural movement}}\n{{About|the contemporary movement|the historical style|Neoclassical architecture}}\n[[File:Chicago Library Downtown.png|thumb|[[Harold Washington Library]] in [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois, USA]], 1991, by [[Thomas H. Beeby|HBRA Architects]]]]\n'''New Classical architecture''', '''New Classicism''' or the '''New Classical movement''' is a contemporary movement in architecture that continues the practice of [[Classical architecture]]. It can be considered as the modern continuation of [[Neoclassical architecture]]<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Curl|first1=James Stevens|author-link1=James Stevens Curl|chapter=New Classicism|chapter-url=https://books.google.it/books?id=4Lu6BwAAQBAJ|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Architecture|last2=Wilson|first2=Susan|date=2015|pages=520\u2013522|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-967498-5|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Curl, James Stevens, 1937-|title=A dictionary of architecture and landscape architecture|date=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|others=Curl, James Stevens, 1937-|isbn=978-0-19-280630-7|edition=2nd|location=Oxford [England]|oclc=64585874}}</ref>. The design and construction of buildings in this tradition is continuous throughout the twentieth and twenty-first centuries, even as [[Modernism|modernist]] and other post-classical theories of architecture have been more dominant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.architecturaldigest.com/story/new-classical-architecture |title=Inside Architecture's New Classicism Boom |last=Quigley |first=Kathleen |website=[[Architectural Digest]] |language=en |access-date=2019-02-16}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:Schermerhorn.jpg|thumb|[[Schermerhorn Symphony Center]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] \u2013 opened in 2006]]\nIn Britain, architect [[Raymond Erith]] continued to design classical houses into the late 1960s and early 1970s. [[Quinlan Terry]], a New Classical Architect who continues to practice, was an employee, later a partner and now the successor of the late [[Raymond Erith]]. In the late 1970s several young architects in Europe began challenging modernist proposals in architecture and planning. To broadcast them, [[Leon Krier]] and [[Maurice Culot]] founded the ''Archives d'Architecture Moderne'' in [[Brussels]] and began publishing texts and counterprojects to modernist proposals in architecture and planning.<ref>Leon Krier and Maurice Culot, \"Counterprojets: Prefaces,\" (Brussels: Archives d'Architecture Moderne, 1980).</ref> It received a boost from the sponsorship of [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], especially with [[The Prince's Foundation for Building Community]].<ref>Charles, Prince of Wales, \"A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture,\" (New York: Doubleday, 1989).</ref>\n\n[[File:Thomas Aquinas Chapel Facade 2.jpg|thumbnail|right|Chapel at [[Thomas Aquinas College]] by [[Duncan Stroik]] (completed in 2009)]]\n\nIn these years, [[postmodern architecture]] developed a critique of modernist architectural aesthetics.<ref name=McAlester>{{cite book|last=McAlester|first=Virginia Savage|title=A Field Guide to American Houses|year=2013|publisher=Alfred A. Knopf|isbn=978-1-4000-4359-0|pages=664\u2013665, 668\u2013669}}</ref>  Among them were certain influential postmodernist architects such as [[Charles Moore (architect)|Charles Moore]], [[Robert Venturi]],<ref>Robert Venturi, \"Complexity and Contradiction in Architecture,\" (New York: Museum of Modern Art, 1966).</ref> and [[Michael Graves]],  who used classical elements as ironic motifs in order to criticize modernism's sterility. A broad spectrum of more than two dozen architects, theorists, and historians presented other alternatives to modernism.<ref>Andreas Papadakis and Harriet Watson, eds., \"New Classicism: Omnibus Volume,\" (London: Academy Editions, 1990).</ref> Among them were several serious New Classical architects who saw classicism as a legitimate mode of architectural expression, several of whom would later become Driehaus Prize Laureates, including some such as [[Thomas Beeby]] and [[Robert A.M. Stern]], who practice both in post modern as well as classical modes. Some postmodernist firms, such as Stern and Albert, Righter, & Tittman, fully moved from postmodern design to new interpretations of traditional architecture.<ref name=\"McAlester\" /> Thomas Gordon Smith, the 1979 Rome Prize laureate from the American Academy in Rome, was a devotee of Charles Moore. In 1988, Smith published \"Classical Architecture - Rule and Invention\", and, in 1989, was appointed to chair of the [[University of Notre Dame]] Department of Architecture, now the School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.nd.edu/classicalarch/2012/09/28/many-canons-many-conversions/|title=Many Canons, Many Conversions -|website=blogs.nd.edu|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184453/http://blogs.nd.edu/classicalarch/2012/09/28/many-canons-many-conversions/|archivedate=29 October 2013}}</ref> Today, other programs exist which teach in part New Classical Architecture at the [[University of Miami]], [[Judson University]], [[Andrews University]] and beginning in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucdenver.edu/academics/colleges/ArchitecturePlanning/Documents/Christine%20Franck%20appointment.pdf |title=College of Architecture and Planning at CU Denver |accessdate=2013-10-26 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191200/http://www.ucdenver.edu/academics/colleges/ArchitecturePlanning/Documents/Christine%20Franck%20appointment.pdf |archivedate=2013-10-29 }}</ref>  the [http://cap.ucdenver.edu/carta Center for Advanced Research in Traditional Architecture] at the University of Colorado Denver.\n\nAlongside these academic and scholarly developments, a populist and professional manifestation of new classicism has existed and continues to develop. The 1963 demolition of [[McKim, Mead & White]]'s [[Pennsylvania Station (1910\u20131963)|Pennsylvania Railroad Station]] in [[New York City]] provoked the formation of [[Classical America]] and its regional chapters, led by [[Henry Hope Reed, Jr.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/on-the-town/how-henry-hope-reed-saved-architecture/17877/|title=How Henry Hope Reed Saved Architecture|website=The New York Sun|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171020164252/http://www.nysun.com/on-the-town/how-henry-hope-reed-saved-architecture/17877|archivedate=20 October 2017}}</ref>  Classical America advocated the appreciation of classically inspired buildings and for the practice of contemporary classical and traditional design by teaching architects to draw the classical orders, hosting walking tours, educational events, conferences and publishing The Classical America Series in Art and Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/classical-america-series-in-art-and-architecture/|title=Books - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620084212/http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/classical-america-series-in-art-and-architecture/|archivedate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, the then-named Institute of Classical Architecture merged with Classical America to form the Institute of Classical Architecture & Classical America (now the [[Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]]). The ICAA currently supports and is supported by regional chapters across the United States, almost all of which host awards programs <ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.classicist.org/?cat=49|title=Articles - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=blog.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20131105150958/http://blog.classicist.org/?cat=49|archivedate=5 November 2013}}</ref> which recognize significant accomplishments in new classical and traditional design and construction.  The ICAA publishes ''[[The Classicist]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/the-classicist/|title=Books - Institute of Classical Architecture & Art|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010011101/http://www.classicist.org/publications-and-bookshop/the-classicist/|archivedate=10 October 2017}}</ref> a peer-reviewed journal exclusively dedicated to the theory and practice of contemporary classicism in architecture, urbanism, and the allied arts.  The ICAA offers educational programs to architecture and design professionals, many of which follow the methodologies of the [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure des Beaux-Arts|\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]]. The ICAA also teaches courses to educate the general public,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicist.org/programs/|title=Calendar|website=www.classicist.org|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013011308/http://www.classicist.org/programs/|archivedate=13 October 2017}}</ref> and has created programs such as the Beaux Arts Atelier, the Advanced Program in Residential Design for the American Institute of Building Designers, and many other unique programs.\n\nThe international character of the New Classical movement was propelled by the creation in 2001 of the [[INTBAU|International Network for Traditional Building, Architecture & Urbanism (INTBAU)]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Staff|first=Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2002/feb/11/artsfeatures|title=Hooked on classics: in praise of traditional architecture|date=2002-02-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>, an international organization dedicated on supporting traditional building and the maintenance of local character<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/info/about-us/|title=About Us {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. INTBAU has over 30 local chapters, which include countries like Albania, Afghanistan, Australia, Bangladesh, Canada, China, Cuba, Cyprus, Czechia, Estonia, Finland, Germany, India, Iran, Ireland, Italy, Malaysia, Montenegro, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Nigeria, Pakistan, the Philippines, Poland, Portugal, Romania, Russia, Spain, Sweden, Turkey and the USA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/info/chapters/|title=Chapters {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>. This network was created under the patronage of [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles of Wales]], himself an important figure in the New Classical movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.coinupdate.com/united-kingdom-new-crown-coin-celebrates-the-70th-birthday-of-hrh-charles-prince-of-wales/|title=United Kingdom: New crown coin celebrates the 70th birthday of HRH Charles, Prince of Wales {{!}} Coin Update|website=news.coinupdate.com|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> \n\nIn 2003, Chicago philanthropist [[Richard H. Driehaus]] established<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interactive.wttw.com/beeby/driehaus|title=The Driehaus Prize|date=7 March 2013|website=wttw.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023041011/http://interactive.wttw.com/beeby/driehaus|archivedate=23 October 2017}}</ref> a prize in architecture to be given to an architect \"whose work embodies the principles of classical and traditional architecture and urbanism in society, and creates a positive, long lasting impact.\"  Awarded by the [[Notre Dame School of Architecture|University of Notre Dame School of Architecture]], the [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]] is seen as the alternative to the modernist [[Pritzker Prize]]. The Driehaus Prize is given in conjunction with the [[Henry Hope Reed Award|Reed Award]], for an individual working outside the practice of architecture who has supported the cultivation of the traditional city, its architecture and art through writing, planning or promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Driehaus Prize Nomination Process|url=http://architecture.nd.edu/about/driehaus-prize/nomination-process/|publisher=University of Notre Dame School of Architecture|accessdate=11 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329102201/http://architecture.nd.edu/about/driehaus-prize/nomination-process/|archivedate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Other high-profiled classical architecture awards are the US-American [[Palladio Award]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Palladio Awards|url=http://www.palladioawards.com/|publisher=Active Interest Media|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140406230208/http://palladioawards.com/|archivedate=6 April 2014}}</ref>, the [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian]] [[Rafael Manzano Prize]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.premiorafaelmanzano.com/en/|title=Premio Rafael Manzano de Nueva Arquitectura Tradicional|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>,  the [[Edmund N. Bacon Prize]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Edmund N. Bacon Prize|url=http://philadelphiacfa.org/lecture-bacon.php|publisher=Philadelphia Center for Architecture|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413172007/http://philadelphiacfa.org/lecture-bacon.php|archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref> and the [[Rieger Graham Prize]]<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rieger Graham Prize|url=http://www.classicist.org/awards-and-prizes/rieger-graham-prize/|publisher=Institute of Classical Architecture & Art in New York|accessdate=10 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413141627/http://www.classicist.org/awards-and-prizes/rieger-graham-prize/|archivedate=13 April 2014}}</ref>  of the [[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]] (ICAA) for architecture graduates.\n\n== Institutions teaching New Classical Architecture ==\n<!--- Please sort alphabetically by location! References for curriculum welcome. --->\nWhile modernist teaching remains dominant at universities and architecture faculties around the world, some institutions focus solely, mainly or partly on teaching the principles of traditional and classical architecture and urban planning. Some of these are:<ref>[http://www.intbau.org/archive/academic.htm INTBAU] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728131429/http://www.intbau.org/archive/academic.htm |date=2015-07-28 }} - A guide to academic institutions/universities teaching New Urbanism and traditional/classical design. Retrieved 10 March 2015.</ref>\n\n;In India\n*Tirumala S.V. Institute of Traditional Sculpture and Architecture (SVITSA) in [[Tirupati]], [[Andhra Pradesh, India|Andhra Pradesh]]<ref>[http://www.tirumala.org Tirumala S.V. Institute of Traditional Sculpture and Architecture (SVITSA) in Tirupati] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202094950/http://www.tirumala.org// |date=2016-02-02 }}, India</ref>\n\n;In Italy\n* [[Polytechnic University of Bari]] in [[Bari]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/|title=Institutions {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n;In New Zealand\n*[[Unitec Institute of Technology|UNITEC Institute of Technology]] in [[Auckland]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/|title=Institutions {{!}} INTBAU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n;In the United Kingdom\n*National Design Academy in [[Nottingham]] (heritage interior design)<ref>[http://www.nda.ac.uk/courses/Foundation-Degree-in-Heritage-Interior-Design.aspx National Design Academy Nottingham] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315035327/http://www.nda.ac.uk/courses/Foundation-Degree-in-Heritage-Interior-Design.aspx |date=2015-03-15 }}, degree course for heritage interior design</ref>\n*[[The Prince's Foundation for Building Community]] in [[London]]\n*[[The Prince's School of Traditional Arts]] in [[London]]\n*Unit 6 of the [[Kingston School of Art]]'s [[Master of Architecture]] program;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fada.kingston.ac.uk/al/march-architecture-unit-6-201516/|title=MArch Architecture \u2013 Unit 6 \u2013 2015/16|quote=''We will engage with the fundamental architectural considerations of scale and language, and the application of the order of classicism at the scale of the town, building, room and fitting.''|accessdate=13 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213165817/http://fada.kingston.ac.uk/al/march-architecture-unit-6-201516/|archivedate=13 February 2017}}</ref> the only postgraduate unit in the United Kingdom to teach classical design. Previously, this was taught in the undergraduate program.\n*[[University of Portsmouth]] in [[Portsmouth]], School of Architecture<ref>[http://www.port.ac.uk/media/contacts-and-departments/arch/project-office/ARCH---Project-Office---CPD---Design-Classical.pdf Portsmouth School of Architecture: Design Classical] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402182836/http://www.port.ac.uk/media/contacts-and-departments/arch/project-office/ARCH---Project-Office---CPD---Design-Classical.pdf |date=2015-04-02 }}. ''The school presents its award-winning course in the elements of classical design and how to\ndesign in the classical idiom, for CPD credits.'', PDF, retrieved 10 March 2015</ref>\n*[[PRASADA - Practice, Research, and Advancement in South Asian Design and Architecture]] at [[Welsh School of Architecture]], [[Cardiff University]] in Cardiff, Wales\n \n;In the United States\n[[File:Selwyn3.jpg|thumb|Ann's Court, [[Selwyn College, Cambridge]] (designed by [[Porphyrios Associates]])]]\n*[[Andrews University#School of Architecture, Art & Design|Andrews University]] in [[Berrien Springs, Michigan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrews.edu/saad/architecture/about/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616090857/http://www.andrews.edu/saad/architecture/about/|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 June 2012|title=Andrews University School of Architecture, Art & Design|quote=''Throughout the educational process, students are challenged to base architectural decisions on thoughtful and learned criteria, including the body of knowledge found within vernacular and classical traditions.''|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref> \n*[[Old Charleston Jail#American College of the Building Arts|American College of the Building Arts]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://buildingartscollege.us/|title=Welcome!|first=Chad|last=Urban|website=buildingartscollege.us|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150331002733/http://buildingartscollege.us/|archivedate=31 March 2015}}</ref> and School of the Arts at [[College of Charleston]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]]\n*The Center for Advanced Research in Traditional Architecture at the [[University of Colorado]] in [[Denver]], Colorado\n*[[Grand Central Academy of Art]] formerly hosted at the [[Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture & Art]] (ICAA) in [[New York City]], New York\n*[[The Institute of Classical Architecture and Art|Institute of Classical Architecture & Art]] (ICAA) in [[New York City]], New York\n*[[Notre Dame School of Architecture|University of Notre Dame School of Architecture]] in [[Notre Dame, Indiana]]\n*Beaux-Arts Academy in [[Salt Lake City]], Utah<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baa-utah.com/about/|title=Beaux-Arts Academy in Salt Lake City, classical architecture study programs|website=baa-utah.com|accessdate=3 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314163529/http://www.baa-utah.com/about/|archivedate=14 March 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Academy of Classical Design]] in Southern Pines, North Carolina\n*[[Utah Valley University]] in [[Orem, Utah]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uvu.edu/aed/architecture/degrees-programs/bs-architecture.html|title=UVU Bachelor of Architecture {{!}} Bachelor of Architecture {{!}} Architecture and Engineering Design|website=www.uvu.edu|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n*[[University of Miami]] in [[Miami|Miami, Florida]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arc.miami.edu/academics/certificates/index.html|title=Certificates {{!}} School of Architecture {{!}} University of Miami|website=arc.miami.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n*[[Yale School of Architecture]] in [[New Haven, Connecticut]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Salingaros, Nikos Angelos.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/57139148|title=Anti-architecture and deconstruction|date=2004|publisher=Umbau-Verlag|others=Alexander, Christopher, 1936-|isbn=3-937954-01-5|location=Solingen, Germany|oclc=57139148}}</ref>\n==Examples==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Richmond_-_panoramio.jpg|[[Richmond, London|Richmond Riverside, London, England]], 1984\u201387, by [[Quinlan Terry]].\nFile:Main Plaza - Frankfurt Main - Germany - 02.jpg|''Main Plaza'', [[Frankfurt|Frankfurt, Germany]] by [[Hans Kollhoff]]\nFile:Brentwood_Cathedral_exterior_2.jpg|[[Brentwood Cathedral]], [[Brentwood, Essex|Brentwood, England]] by [[Quinlan Terry]]\nFile:Basshall.JPG|[[Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall]], [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth, Texas, USA]], 1998, by [[David M. Schwarz]]\nFile:Guadalupe_Shrine_Front.jpg|[[Shrine of Our Lady of Guadalupe]], [[La Crosse, Wisconsin|La Crosse, Wisconsin, USA]], 2004\u20132008, by [[Duncan G. Stroik]]\nFile:Queen_Mother_SQUARE,_Poundbury,_Dorset.jpg|[[Poundbury|Poundbury, England]], 1993, by [[L\u00e9on Krier]]\nFile:Moscow (8351273413).jpg|[[Ritz-Carlton Hotel Moscow|Ritz-Carlton Hotel]], [[Moscow|Moscow, Russia]], 2007, by Meerson Architects\nFile:Dallas Meadows Museum 1.jpg|[[Meadows Museum]], [[Dallas|Dallas, Texas, USA]], 2001, by [[Thomas H. Beeby|HBRA Architects]]\nFile:2013-05-12_London_RAF_Bomber_Command_Memorial.jpg|[[RAF Bomber Command Memorial|Royal Air Force Bomber Command Memorial]], [[London|London, England]], 2012, by Liam O'Connor\nFile:Entrance_of_Queen's_Gallery,_Buckingham_Palace_(cropped).jpg|[[Queen's Gallery]], [[London|London, England]], 2002, by [[John Simpson (architect)|John Simpson]]\nFile:Downing College in bright daylight.jpg|[[Downing College|Maitland Robinson Library]], [[Cambridge|Cambridge, England]], 1992, by [[Quinlan Terry]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture}}\n*[[New Urbanism]]\n*[[Revivalism (architecture)]]\n*[[Classical Realism]]\n*[[Driehaus Architecture Prize]]\n*[[Vernacular architecture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Alexander|first=Christopher|title=The Timeless Way of Building|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H6CE9hlbO8sC|year=1979|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-502402-9}}\n*{{cite book|author=Charles, Prince of Wales|title=A Vision of Britain: A Personal View of Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_FFIAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=978-0-385-26903-2}}\n*{{cite book|last=Coles|first=William A.|title=Architecture in America: A Battle of Styles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vc4ZKS5uLNYC|year=1961|publisher=Ardent Media}}\n*{{cite book|last=Curl|first=James Stevens|title=Classical Architecture: An Introduction to Its Vocabulary and Essentials, with a Select Glossary of Terms|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ub5D8cyl2AAC|year=2003|publisher=Norton|isbn=978-0-393-73119-4}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dodd|first=Phillip James|title=The Art of Classical Details: Theory, Design and Craftsmanship|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tzlv-bsMT3kC|year=2013|publisher=Images Publishing|isbn=978-1-86470-203-3}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dowling|first=Elizabeth Meredith|title=New Classicism: The Rebirth of Traditional Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tsdPAAAAMAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Random House Incorporated|isbn=978-0-8478-2660-5}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gabriel|first=J. Fran\u00e7ois|title=Classical Architecture for the Twenty-first Century: An Introduction to Design|url=https://archive.org/details/classicalarchite0000gabr|url-access=registration|year=2004|publisher=W.W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-73076-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gromort|first=Georges|title=The Elements of Classical Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4qp61EfFbzEC|year=2001|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-73051-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=Krier|first=L\u00e9on|title=Albert Speer: architecture, 1932-1942|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mE03AQAAIAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Archives d'architecture moderne}}\n*{{cite book|last=Matrana|first=Marc R.|title=Lost Plantations of the South|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D1YfPjRCucQC|year=2009|publisher=Univ. Press of Mississippi|isbn=978-1-60473-469-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reed|first=Henry Hope|title=The Golden City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3kfFslzS50YC|date=1971|publisher=W.W. Norton|isbn=978-0-393-00547-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Scully|first=Vincent Joseph|title=The shingle style today: or, The historian's revenge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=41xUAAAAMAAJ|year=1974|publisher=G. Braziller}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stroik|first=Duncan|title=The Church Building as a Sacred Place: Beauty, Transcendence, and the Eternal|year=2012|publisher=Liturgy Training Publications|isbn=978-1-59525-037-7}}\n*{{cite book|last=Summerson|first=John|title=The Classical Language of Architecture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=57aoJE26kQkC|year=1963|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-69012-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Watkin|first=David|title=Morality and Architecture|url=https://archive.org/details/moralityarchitec0000watk|url-access=registration|year=1977|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-817350-2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Commons category-inline|Neoclassical architecture}}\n* [http://www.doric-column.com/glossary_classical_architecture.html ''Illustrated Glossary of Classical Architecture'']\n* [http://www.classicist.org Institute of Classical Architecture and Art]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130609040947/http://www.traditionalarchitecture.co.uk/index.html Traditional Architecture Group]\n* [http://www.intbau.org/resources/institutions/  INTBAU - Universities / institutions offering traditional architecture courses by country]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCco_r00ZJQ_46P5GPYguIvA/videos OpenSource Classicism] - project for free educational content about (new) classical architecture\n* [https://www.spectator.co.uk/2017/10/the-architectural-trads-are-back-we-should-celebrate/ ''The architectural traditions are back \u2013 we should celebrate''], [[The Spectator]], Hugh Pearman, 28 October 2017\n\n;Examples\n* [https://www.flickr.com/groups/neohistorism/ Neohistorism Photo Group - New Classic Architecture]\n\n{{Archhistory}